# Part I

Syft reported 8 components while Trivy reported 8. I noticed that Syft includes a “relationships” array that defines how components relate to each other while Trivy stores a “dependencies” array that shows which components depend on which other components.

# Reflection

This assignment revealed some of the challenges in compiling accurate software and hardware bill of materials and understanding how they interact. I hadn't fully considered the effects of hardware risks on the corresponding software components. I feel that many organizations move so fast in their development of products that they are unable (or unwilling) to compile extensive reports on the attack surfaces of those products. Automated tools that compule SBOMs and identify vulnerabilities are a good first step in bridging that gap.
